User & Access ManagementRemove Unauthorized Users

Open Terminal (Ctrl+Alt+T)
List all users: cat /etc/passwd | grep "/bin/bash"
Compare with README authorized users list
Remove unauthorized user: sudo deluser <username>
Remove user home directory: sudo rm -rf /home/<username>
Check for UID 0 Users (Root Privileges)

In Terminal: awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd
Only "root" should appear
If other users appear: sudo usermod -u <new_uid> <username>
Disable Guest Account

Open terminal
Create/edit file: sudo nano /etc/lightdm/lightdm.conf
Add under [Seat:*] section:

   allow-guest=false

Save (Ctrl+X, Y, Enter)
Restart LightDM: sudo systemctl restart lightdm
Set Password Policies

Install password quality tools: sudo apt-get install libpam-pwquality
Edit PAM config: sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-password
Find line with pam_pwquality.so and modify:

   password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3 minlen=8 difok=3 ucredit=-1 lcredit=-1 dcredit=-1 ocredit=-1

minlen=8 (minimum 8 characters)
ucredit=-1 (require uppercase)
lcredit=-1 (require lowercase)
dcredit=-1 (require digit)
ocredit=-1 (require special character)


Save and exit
Configure Password Aging

Edit login.defs: sudo nano /etc/login.defs
Set these values:

   PASS_MAX_DAYS 90
   PASS_MIN_DAYS 7
   PASS_WARN_AGE 14

Apply to existing users: sudo chage -M 90 -m 7 -W 14 <username>
Check settings: sudo chage -l <username>
Remove Unauthorized Sudo Users

Check sudo group: grep sudo /etc/group
Remove user from sudo: sudo deluser <username> sudo
Check sudoers file: sudo visudo
Check sudoers.d directory: ls -la /etc/sudoers.d/
Remove unauthorized files: sudo rm /etc/sudoers.d/<filename>
Lock Unnecessary System Accounts

List accounts: cat /etc/passwd
Lock accounts like games, irc, etc: sudo usermod -L <username>
Set shell to nologin: sudo usermod -s /usr/sbin/nologin <username>
Authentication & PasswordsChange All User Passwords

For each authorized user: sudo passwd <username>
Enter strong password (meet complexity requirements)
Change root password: sudo passwd root
Enable Automatic Security Updates

Open Software Updater from Menu
Click Settings → Updates tab
Set "When there are security updates" to "Download and install automatically"
Or via terminal: sudo dpkg-reconfigure -plow unattended-upgrades
Select "Yes"
Check for Blank Passwords

View shadow file: sudo cat /etc/shadow
Look for entries with ! or * between first and second colon
Entries with :: have blank passwords - set password immediately
Services & ProcessesList and Disable Unauthorized Services

List all services: systemctl list-unit-files --type=service | grep enabled
Check service status: systemctl status <service-name>
Stop service: sudo systemctl stop <service-name>
Disable service: sudo systemctl disable <service-name>
Common services to check: vsftpd, telnet, apache2, nginx, samba
Remove Prohibited Software

List installed packages: dpkg --list | less
Search for specific software: dpkg --list | grep -i <package-name>
Common prohibited items: wireshark, nmap, john, hydra, netcat, telnet, games
Remove package: sudo apt-get purge <package-name>
Check for games: dpkg --list | grep -i game
Remove games: sudo apt-get purge aisleriot gnome-mahjongg gnome-mines gnome-sudoku
Check for Backdoors/Listeners

List listening ports: sudo netstat -tulpn | grep LISTEN
Check for netcat: ps aux | grep nc
Kill suspicious processes: sudo kill -9 <PID>
Remove netcat: sudo apt-get purge netcat netcat-traditional
Review Startup Applications

Menu → Preferences → Startup Applications
Disable unauthorized startup items
Check crontabs: sudo crontab -l and crontab -l
Check all user crontabs: sudo ls /var/spool/cron/crontabs
Edit if needed: sudo crontab -e
File System SecurityFind World-Writable Files

Search system: sudo find / -perm -002 -type f -ls 2>/dev/null
Remove write permission: sudo chmod o-w <filename>
Locate Media Files (if prohibited)

Find audio files: sudo find /home -name "*.mp3" -o -name "*.wav" 2>/dev/null
Find video files: sudo find /home -name "*.mp4" -o -name "*.avi" -o -name "*.mov" 2>/dev/null
Find images: sudo find /home -name "*.jpg" -o -name "*.png" 2>/dev/null
Delete if prohibited: sudo rm <filepath>
Check Crontabs for Malicious Tasks

System crontab: sudo cat /etc/crontab
Cron directories: ls /etc/cron.*
Check each: sudo cat /etc/cron.d/*, /etc/cron.daily/*, etc.
Remove malicious entries: sudo rm <filepath> or edit files
Review Hosts File

Check hosts: sudo cat /etc/hosts
Edit if needed: sudo nano /etc/hosts
Remove suspicious entries
Should only contain localhost entries typically
Firewall & NetworkEnable UFW Firewall

Check status: sudo ufw status
Enable firewall: sudo ufw enable
Set default deny: sudo ufw default deny incoming
Set default allow: sudo ufw default allow outgoing
Allow necessary services: sudo ufw allow <port>/<protocol>
Check rules: sudo ufw status numbered
Configure SSH Properly

Edit SSH config: sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Set these parameters:

   PermitRootLogin no
   PasswordAuthentication yes
   PermitEmptyPasswords no
   Protocol 2
   Port 2222 (or leave 22 if required)

Restart SSH: sudo systemctl restart sshd
If SSH not needed and not required: sudo systemctl disable sshd
Check Listening Ports

View all listening: sudo netstat -tulpn
Or use ss: sudo ss -tulpn
Investigate unknown services
Close unnecessary ports via firewall or disable service
